subject: Add CoreCount to ProcessorSummary
commitMessage:
Add CoreCount to ProcessorSummary

In Redfish ComputerSystem schema, the ProcessorSummary parameter
lists summary information of the Processors on the system. This commit
adds the 'CoreCount' property to ProcessorSummary.

Testing:

1. Redfish Validator Testing successfully passed.
2. Curl testing:

curl -k -H "X-Auth-Token: $tok" https://$bmc/redfish/v1/Systems/system

...
  "ProcessorSummary": {
    "CoreCount": 24,
    "Count": 2,
    "Status": {
      "Health": "OK",
      "HealthRollup": "OK",
      "State": "Disabled"
    }
  },
...

Signed-off-by: Ali Ahmed <ama213000@gmail.com>
Change-Id: Idda4f20bd1bb3f5002791ad20787979c632ed5f0

This patchset seems to be mapping, "family" to Model, which doesn't really seem right to me.  Wouldn't Family be mapped to EffectiveFamily, and Asset.Model would be mapped to "Model"?

Only downside of splitting commits up later is sometimes we lose comments. 

From https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/44564/9//COMMIT_MSG#18

Ed Tanous
This seems like it would have a race condition if the models are different.  Also, the redfish schema for this states:

"The processor model for the primary or majority of processors in this system."
and
"This property shall contain the processor model for the central processors in the system, per the description in the Processor Information - Processor Family section of the SMBIOS Specification DSP0134 2.8 or later"

Jonathan Doman
> > Are we sure this model number matches up to the SMBIOS specification?

> Is it really up to bmcweb to enforce this? 
I thought if your data is wrong on D-Bus (e.g. an empty PartNumber) we just put it out on Redfish.

I think the point is this commit changes Model to pull from Inventory.Decorator.Asset.Model instead of Inventory.Item.Cpu.Family as it was doing before. On Intel systems using smbios-mdr to provide this data on D-Bus, ony the latter is a model string which matches up to the options in the SMBIOS spec. As Ed quoted, I think Redfish spec implies the current behavior is more correct.

FWIW, I have an open issue with DMTF about something related to this.  There seems to be the EffectiveFamily property for the hex version of this, but no Family property that this would normally be loaded in.

Part of me wonders if that's a typo, or was on purpose.  Mapping the property called "model" to family, when there's a separate EffectiveFamily property, and a differently defined "Model" property on the processor itself, seems really odd.  As a user, I would've expected ProcessorSummary.Model for a given system to match Processor.Model for the processors in the system, but the way the descriptions read, that's not the case.  On the simple-rack-mounted-server mockup, Processor.Model puts the string version of the table 22 processor family in the Processor.Model resource, which I don't think is what we did on OpenBMC initially.  Maybe that's some of the issue?

I would like this to get in, even without this "Model". Should just remove? 
Add a TODO, "TODO: Get Model"?
Sure, if we want to remove the Model changes from the patch until we have more input from DMTF, that seems reasonable.
Done
